–1369","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Overleden","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1315–1369":"1315–1369","7 Mar 1399":"7 maart 1399","1363":"1363","4 July 1369":"4 juli 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England",", York, England":"York, North Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Aston, Derbyshire, England":"Coal Aston, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1350–7 Mar 1399":"1350–7 March 1399","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1338–1369":"1338–1369","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Deceased","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1315–1369":"1315–1369","7 Mar 1399":"7 March 1399","1363":"1363","4 July 1369":"4 July 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England",", York, England":"York, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Aston, Derbyshire, England":"Coal Aston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Melton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, all of which have the same origin as   Middleton  , with Old English <i>middel</i> replaced by its Old Norse equivalent <i>methal</i> after the Scandinavian settlement of northern and eastern England."],"variants":[{"name":"Middleton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richardus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Richard  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare   Rickards  .","German: patronymic from the personal name   Richard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Richard","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Richardus Melton was born in 1350, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir William de Melton, was 33 and his mother, Joan Lucy, was 36. He had at least 2 sons with Elizabeth Everingham. He died on 7 March 1399, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1350–7 Mar 1399":"1350–7. märts 1399","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1338–1369":"1338–1369","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Surnud","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1315–1369":"1315–1369","7 Mar 1399":"7. märts 1399","1363":"1363","4 July 1369":"4. juuli 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England",", York, England":"York, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aston, Derbyshire, England":"Coal Aston, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1350–7 Mar 1399":"1350–7. maaliskuuta 1399","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1338–1369":"1338–1369","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Kuollut","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1315–1369":"1315–1369","7 Mar 1399":"7. maaliskuuta 1399","1363":"1363","4 July 1369":"4. heinäkuuta 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England",", York, England":"York, North Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aston, Derbyshire, England":"Coal Aston, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1350–7 Mar 1399":"1350–7 mars 1399","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1338–1369":"1338–1369","1363–1455":"1363–1455","1367–Male":"1367–Décédé","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1315–1369":"1315–1369","7 Mar 1399":"7 mars 1399","1363":"1363","4 July 1369":"4 juillet 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1317":"1317